{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Q8MYhfA449m4ArtRUX539T","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→These instances are from the main, weighted, anytime track of the MaxSAT 2024 competition.\n     2→\n     3→FORMAT: WCNF (2022+ format)\n     4→\n     5→The instances use the new WCNF format (post-2022). Key differences from the old format:\n     6→- There is NO p-line (no \"p wcnf ...\" header).\n     7→- Hard clauses start with `h`, followed by literals, terminated by `0`.\n     8→- Soft clauses start with their integer weight, followed by literals, terminated by `0`.\n     9→- Comment lines start with `c`. Each file has a JSON comment header with instance statistics (nvars, ncls, clause length stats, weight stats, etc.).\n    10→\n    11→Example hard clause:  h 3 -5 7 0       (must be satisfied)\n    12→Example soft clause:  42 -1 3 0         (weight 42, adds 42 to cost if falsified)\n    13→\n    14→Some instances have no hard clauses at all (nhards: 0) — in that case every clause is soft.\n    15→\n    16→COST DEFINITION:\n    17→\n    18→A valid solution is an assignment of all variables to true/false that satisfies ALL hard clauses.\n    19→The cost of a solution = sum of weights of all FALSIFIED soft clauses.\n    20→The goal is to minimize this cost.\n    21→A solution that violates any hard clause is invalid.\n    22→\n    23→INSTANCE STATISTICS:\n    24→\n    25→The comment header at the top of each .wcnf file contains useful metadata in JSON format:\n    26→- nvars: number of variables\n    27→- ncls: total number of clauses\n    28→- nhards / nsofts: number of hard / soft clauses\n    29→- nhard_len_stats / nsoft_len_stats: clause length statistics\n    30→- nsoft_wts: number of distinct soft clause weights\n    31→- soft_wt_stats: weight distribution statistics (min, max, avg, stddev)\n    32→\n    33→best-costs.csv: one row per instance. Columns: instance, best_cost. A best_cost of -1 means no known solution.\n    34→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8ed653bb-a3ea-4630-9552-a8c96528784c","uuid":"846a0b50-1fde-4cdf-9337-a67fe552fe2f","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/agent-sat-3/benchmarks/max-sat-2024/instructions.txt","content":"These instances are from the main, weighted, anytime track of the MaxSAT 2024 competition.\n\nFORMAT: WCNF (2022+ format)\n\nThe instances use the new WCNF format (post-2022). Key differences from the old format:\n- There is NO p-line (no \"p wcnf ...\" header).\n- Hard clauses start with `h`, followed by literals, terminated by `0`.\n- Soft clauses start with their integer weight, followed by literals, terminated by `0`.\n- Comment lines start with `c`. Each file has a JSON comment header with instance statistics (nvars, ncls, clause length stats, weight stats, etc.).\n\nExample hard clause:  h 3 -5 7 0       (must be satisfied)\nExample soft clause:  42 -1 3 0         (weight 42, adds 42 to cost if falsified)\n\nSome instances have no hard clauses at all (nhards: 0) — in that case every clause is soft.\n\nCOST DEFINITION:\n\nA valid solution is an assignment of all variables to true/false that satisfies ALL hard clauses.\nThe cost of a solution = sum of weights of all FALSIFIED soft clauses.\nThe goal is to minimize this cost.\nA solution that violates any hard clause is invalid.\n\nINSTANCE STATISTICS:\n\nThe comment header at the top of each .wcnf file contains useful metadata in JSON format:\n- nvars: number of variables\n- ncls: total number of clauses\n- nhards / nsofts: number of hard / soft clauses\n- nhard_len_stats / nsoft_len_stats: clause length statistics\n- nsoft_wts: number of distinct soft clause weights\n- soft_wt_stats: weight distribution statistics (min, max, avg, stddev)\n\nbest-costs.csv: one row per instance. Columns: instance, best_cost. A best_cost of -1 means no known solution.\n","numLines":34,"startLine":1,"totalLines":34}}}
