{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_0148bWrTS6rAXBpAA176gMCL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Setcover has a unique structure - very few hard clauses (507-4872) but huge number of soft clauses (47K-1M). Greedy SAT doesn't work because nsofts is huge. CWLS didn't improve either since these already seem stuck at local optima.\n\nThe key issue with setcover is that there are too many soft clauses for greedy SAT but too few hard clauses for the problems to be structurally complex. This is a set cover problem - maybe a specialized set cover solver would help?\n\nLet me focus on the bigger opportunities:\n1. Haplotyping (12x) - CWLS should help\n\n\n2. Correlation clustering (2-2.6x) - CWLS\n3. Polysite-bloat (66x) - WPM1 since it has only 5986 unit soft clauses which should be ideal for WPM1\n4. ParametricRBAC domino instances (2-2.4x)\n\nI'll run these one at a time to avoid memory issues. For timetabling, the greedy SAT result of 150 for comp02 versus the current 66 suggests that approach is actually worse, so I need to explore different strategies there.\n\nThe comp02 instance has around 2000 soft clauses and 112K variables, which makes greedy SAT expensive since it iterates over all softs. The existing core-guided solution at cost 66 is already better than what greedy SAT produced. For these timetabling instances, tabu search with more time or CWLS might help, though CWLS didn't improve things either. So I'm focusing on the polysite-bloat instance with WPM1 since the unit soft structure should work well, haplotyping with CWLS from the existing best solution, and correlation clustering.\n\nI'll also try walksat-soft combined with CWLS on the parametric RBAC domino instance. Running these sequentially to avoid memory issues.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":580,"cache_read_input_tokens":84686,"cache_creation":{"ep