{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_017JRcP1XxwzEbg6ybcaZq9n","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good progress! Down to 24 over-2x instances (from 30 earlier). Let me focus on the most tractable ones.\n\nKey targets still:\n1. **decision-tree** (2.05-2.69x, 3 instances): These have 268-765 soft clauses. Randomized greedy didn't help much. Maybe I need to try greedy with different solver backends (g4 vs cd19).2. **timetabling** (2.25-3.34x, 3 instances): ~1500-2000 softs. Hard.\n3. **synplicate** (2.01-2.32x, 2 instances): Try more core-guided-budget4. **correlation-clustering Ionosphere** (2.04x): 10K+ softs5. \n**setcover** (2.07-2.12x): ~1M softs, too many for greedy. **abstraction-refinement downcast-pmd** (2.08x). **polysite-bloat** (2.39x): Need to get from 86 to ~36.\n\nFor the decision-tree instances, I should experiment with glucose4 instead of CaDiCaL—the expert notes suggest CaDiCaL is generally stronger, but these particular instances might respond better to a different solver. Let me think through a more targeted approach for decision-tree rather than just swapping backends.\n\nThese instances have 268-765 softs, which means randomized greedy could run multiple trials, but the real constraint is SAT solver time—each call on 270K variables and 2.5M clauses takes roughly 0.5s, so a full trial of 765 softs balloons to around 382s, which blows past the budget. Scaling this up from the causal_n7 results where each trial took 2-3s, I'm looking at maybe 30-60s per trial on decision-tree, which gives me only 4-8 trials before hitting limits.\n\nBut the sweep data shows randomized greedy actually did help one decision-tree instance—heart-cleveland improved from 229 to 224—so the approach is viable, just constrained by the solver overhead.\n\nI should focus on running more targeted randomized greedy with extended budgets on the worst decision-tree instances, and for synplicate_dag_run2_12 with its 989 unit-weight softs, core-guided-budget with higher budgets might be more effective. I could also try swapping in glucose4 as the solver backend instead of CaDiCaL to see if different solvers produce better solutions, or run the standard greedy_sat function multiple times with different backends rather than spinning up new solvers each time with randomized greedy.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1629,"cache_read_input_tokens":157254,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1629,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8ed653bb-a3ea-4630-9552-a8c96528784c","uuid":"30fc1b66-af95-4056-aa8a-5c7073c53338"}
